<section header="0" xid="1" props="page-margin-right:1.000000in; columns:1; page-margin-header:0.500000in; page-margin-left:1.000000in; column-gap:0.250000in; dom-dir:ltr; text-align:left; page-margin-footer:0.500000in; page-margin-top:1.000000in; page-margin-bottom:1.000000in">
<p style="Normal" xid="2" props="font-family:Times New Roman; dom-dir:ltr; font-style:normal; margin-left:0.0000in; lang:en-US; margin-bottom:0.0000in; text-indent:0.0000in; text-position:normal; margin-top:0.0000in; font-weight:normal; margin-right:0.0000in; text-decoration:none; text-align:left; line-height:2.000000; font-size:12pt"><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; lang:en-US; text-position:normal; font-weight:normal; font-style:normal; text-decoration:none">Edgar Tejada</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="3" props="font-family:Times New Roman; dom-dir:ltr; font-style:normal; margin-left:0.0000in; lang:en-US; margin-bottom:0.0000in; text-indent:0.0000in; text-position:normal; margin-top:0.0000in; font-weight:normal; margin-right:0.0000in; text-decoration:none; text-align:left; line-height:2.000000; font-size:12pt"><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; lang:en-US; text-position:normal; font-weight:normal; font-style:normal; text-decoration:none">Dr. Kelly</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="4" props="font-family:Times New Roman; dom-dir:ltr; font-style:normal; margin-left:0.0000in; lang:en-US; margin-bottom:0.0000in; text-indent:0.0000in; text-position:normal; margin-top:0.0000in; font-weight:normal; margin-right:0.0000in; text-decoration:none; text-align:left; line-height:2.000000; font-size:12pt"><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; lang:en-US; text-position:normal; font-weight:normal; font-style:normal; text-decoration:none">Writing 114: Environmental Writing</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="5" props="font-family:Times New Roman; dom-dir:ltr; font-style:normal; margin-left:0.0000in; lang:en-US; margin-bottom:0.0000in; text-indent:0.0000in; text-position:normal; margin-top:0.0000in; font-weight:normal; margin-right:0.0000in; text-decoration:none; text-align:left; line-height:2.000000; font-size:12pt"><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; lang:en-US; text-position:normal; font-weight:normal; font-style:normal; text-decoration:none">13 May 2020</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="6" props="font-family:Times New Roman; dom-dir:ltr; font-style:normal; margin-left:0.0000in; lang:en-US; margin-bottom:0.0000in; text-indent:0.0000in; text-position:normal; margin-top:0.0000in; font-weight:bold; margin-right:0.0000in; text-decoration:none; text-align:center; line-height:2.000000; font-size:12pt"><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; lang:en-US; text-position:normal; font-weight:bold; font-style:normal; text-decoration:none">The Day the EPA Died</c><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; lang:en-US; text-position:normal; font-weight:normal; font-style:normal; text-decoration:none">	</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="7" props="font-family:Times New Roman; dom-dir:ltr; font-style:normal; margin-left:0.0000in; lang:en-US; margin-bottom:0.0000in; text-indent:0.0000in; text-position:normal; margin-top:0.0000in; font-weight:normal; margin-right:0.0000in; text-decoration:none; text-align:left; line-height:2.000000; font-size:12pt"><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; lang:en-US; text-position:normal; font-weight:normal; font-style:normal; text-decoration:none">	It was an seemingly normal, dystopian day in late March of 2020 like any other day of that year, as the death toll for the Covid-19 was on the rise and uncertainty and fear were clouding the judgment of the American people. I was dealing with my own unclear situations as to where I should live and what directions I could move in as I was graduating from university into a gridlocked economy. Of course, my struggles as a person and the loss of loved ones resonated with everyone, but there was a much bigger death on that Thursday afternoon. It was a death I only recently came to grief, as the Environmental Protection Agency was pronounced dead at the age of 49 years old after a fatal blow that March 26th, 2020 at 14:57 PDT.</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="11" props="font-family:Times New Roman; dom-dir:ltr; font-style:normal; margin-left:0.0000in; lang:en-US; margin-bottom:0.0000in; text-indent:0.0000in; text-position:normal; margin-top:0.0000in; font-weight:normal; margin-right:0.0000in; text-decoration:none; text-align:left; line-height:2.000000; font-size:12pt"><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; lang:en-US; text-position:normal; font-weight:normal; font-style:normal; text-decoration:none">	On that day, the body of the EPA was defanged and desecrated after years of slowly being poisoned by Trump appointed leaders. It was through a memo that the Trump administration announced that the EPA, henceforth, “[W]</c><c>ouldn’t go after companies that fail to satisfy many ‘routine monitoring and reporting obligations’ because of the coronavirus, as long as they documented why they couldn’t fulfill the mandates” (Dlouhy 1). This was, of course, after years of those same Trump appointees all undermining the mission statement of the EPA. These vectors of death</c><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; color:000000; text-decoration:none; text-position:normal; font-weight:normal; font-style:normal; lang:en-US"> rolled back half a century’s worth of protections and standards for maintaining water and air quality at the thundering applause of record breaking stock prices and a never ending bull market. Those stock gains came and went, but the silent poisoning of the EPA finally ended that fateful Thursday. After an onslaught of necrotic chocking to its funding, to the past commitments to Superfund contamination sites, and to the end of car emission goals, the organization’s suffering ended abruptly (Stevens). No longer was there the false pretense that the EPA’s corpse should be protecting our natural resources against the wishes of the President or vested corporate interests. Instead, this murder happened under the perfect conditions to go unnoticed, to be forgotten and allow the American public to be gaslighted into a new, toxic normal.</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="18" props="font-family:Times New Roman; dom-dir:ltr; font-style:normal; margin-left:0.0000in; lang:en-US; text-decoration:none; text-indent:0.0000in; text-position:normal; margin-top:0.0000in; font-weight:normal; line-height:2.000000; margin-bottom:0.0000in; font-size:12pt; margin-right:0.0000in; text-align:left"><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; color:000000; text-decoration:none; text-position:normal; font-weight:normal; font-style:normal; lang:en-US">	Make no mistake, the killing of the Environmental Protection Agency was an act of malice and cowardice. While millions of American’s were unemployed, thousands were dead, and the prospects of recovery were the focus of media outlets, the Trump administration took advantage of the chaos and uncertainty to destroy a regulatory body that had long stood in the way of stripping the nations resources (</c><c>Southerland</c><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; color:000000; text-decoration:none; text-position:normal; font-weight:normal; font-style:normal; lang:en-US">). Instead of fighting against years of proven environmental standards through the grueling process of revoking laws through Congress, the President used powers reserved for emergency situations as a smokescreen for permanent deregulation. Many states have fought back and sued the administration’s abuse, decrying that the “</c><c>EPA’s so-called non-enforcement policy is an illegal abdication of the agency’s statutory responsibilities</c><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; color:000000; text-decoration:none; text-position:normal; font-weight:normal; font-style:normal; lang:en-US">” (</c><c>Larson</c><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; color:000000; text-decoration:none; text-position:normal; font-weight:normal; font-style:normal; lang:en-US">). Unfortunately, I think these attempts at resuscitation of the body are too little too late, as the core has rotted beyond repair.</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="12" props="font-family:Times New Roman; dom-dir:ltr; font-style:normal; margin-left:0.0000in; lang:en-US; margin-bottom:0.0000in; text-indent:0.0000in; text-position:normal; margin-top:0.0000in; font-weight:normal; margin-right:0.0000in; text-decoration:none; text-align:left; line-height:2.000000; font-size:12pt"><c>	So, on that morbid and horrifying note, let’s consider </c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="13" props="font-family:Times New Roman; dom-dir:ltr; font-style:normal; margin-left:0.0000in; lang:en-US; margin-bottom:0.0000in; text-indent:0.0000in; text-position:normal; margin-top:0.0000in; font-weight:normal; margin-right:0.0000in; text-decoration:none; text-align:left; line-height:2.000000; font-size:12pt"><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; lang:en-US; text-position:normal; font-weight:normal; font-style:normal; text-decoration:none"></c></p>
</section>
